    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect MCS selection not matching channel quality or UE capability downstream of `unpack_ul_tti_pdu_list_value`\n\n### Summary\nThe UL TTI request handler in the gNB NFAPI module incorrectly interprets MCS parameters for PUSCH transmissions due to a type mismatch in the PUSCH PDU structure definition. This causes the gNB to select MCS values that don't match the reported channel quality or UE capabilities, leading to either throughput degradation or excessive retransmissions.\n\nThe issue manifests when the gNB receives UL scheduling commands from the CU/DU split, where the `unpack_ul_tti_pdu_list_value` function processes PUSCH PDUs. Due to an incorrect structure member type, the maintenance parameters (which influence TB size calculations and LDPC base graph selection) are misinterpreted, causing downstream MCS selection logic to operate on corrupted data.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Configure OAI gNB with CU/DU split using NFAPI interface\n2. Connect a UE that reports varying channel qualities \n3. Initiate uplink traffic with adaptive MCS enabled\n4. Observe that selected MCS indices don't correlate with reported CQI\n5. Monitor for increased BLER or reduced throughput compared to expected values\n\nIn some cases, this can also lead to segmentation faults when the incorrectly interpreted maintenance parameters cause buffer overflows during TB size calculations.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/public_inc/nfapi_nr_interface_scf.h`: Corrected PUSCH PDU structure to use `nfapi_v3_pusch_maintenance_parameters_t` instead of `nfapi_v3_pdsch_maintenance_parameters_t` at line 1352.\n"
}